    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "## Problem\n\nhttps://old.reddit.com/r/neovim/comments/1mz3wb6/what_the_emacs_minibuffer_is_and_why_neovim_could/ raises an interesting idea: \n\n> In Emacs, there’s this thing called the minibuffer. It’s just a regular buffer that Emacs uses for commands, prompts, and interactive input which expands what we would call the 'cmdheight', pushing the statusline up and displaying content. \n>\n> It creates a unified interface. Instead of having one plugin open a floating popup for fuzzy file search, another showing a completion menu at the bottom, and yet another drawing a quickfix list in a split, many things can use the minibuffer. That means:\n>\n> - Running commands with completion.\n> - Fuzzy finding files or buffers.\n> - Even interactive plugin UIs (think Telescope, fzf, etc).\n\n\nWith Nvim 0.12 + ui2 (`vim._core.ui2`) enabled, cmdline and pager are real buffers. But we might still be missing a \"unified interface\".\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nSomething analogous to `:help preview-window`: \n\n- Establish a global, unified concept for collecting input (cmdline, fuzzy-finding and executing an action based on that input.\n- Third-party plugins can \"provide\" interfaces (fuzzy-finding, completion) in this unified concept.\n\nTo keep the door open for this, do we need to change anything in the `ui2` interface before release? @luukvbaal \n\nNote: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/660 is related, but the goal of this issue is much more constrained: just establish the standard mechanism for presenting these things.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "\n> > In Emacs, there’s this thing called the minibuffer. It’s just a regular buffer that Emacs uses for commands, prompts, and interactive input which expands what we would call the 'cmdheight', pushing the statusline up and displaying content.\n\nJust to confirm, since you mentioned minibuffer in emacs, does this plan will also include a full buffer edit layer on cmdline expected? perhaps if it does we can add #30340 to expected behavior since that's part of things should be done to make cmdline more like a real buffer as well as cmdwin.\n",
