            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "I wanted to create a similar issue and stumbled on this one. \n\nA few workflows are currently very impractical with the cmdline and messages pager being their own things and which such a change would make miles easier.\n1. Copy errors messages. This is probably one of the biggest newbie hurdle. I would very much appreciate in the future an option to make the messages pager a persistent regular buffer.\n2. Copying a command you're typing (possible through C-f or q: although it should probably be the default behaviour?)\n3. Switching from the editing buffer to the cmdline without losing your command (same as above)\n4. Running non-interactive shell commands from neovim and navigating their output.\n\nThe 4th point is the one that I have the most gripes with. I just love neovim but I just can't run my compile commands there unless I use :make and pipe the results into the qflist (which is not the intended usage of the qflist in my understanding. Qflist is made to show errors matching efm). I have to use heavy plugins for simple tasks and I almost always have to use a multiplexer to run git related commands (or a term buffet which I don't like to use)\n\nFurthermore, the qflist and loclist are bizarre buffers with custom behaviours that could be harmonized. By default copen or lopen opens necessarily in a split. You can't :bnext or :bprev to those buffers. You also can't create an arbitrary amount of loclists as they are bound to one per window.\n\nAside from neovim's backwarsq compatibility goal, I'd say that philosophically cmdline mode really has no reason to be a separate mode. It should really be insert mode in a special buffer.",
